> Basically, you can&#x27;t always parse a Perl program without running it.<p>That is true, but what the grandparent said is not: <a href="https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=8626454" rel="nofollow">https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=8626454</a><p>To expand on this, I think a succinct way of summarizing the issue is: you might have to run BEGIN blocks in Perl to parse the non-BEGIN-block part of the program.  The canonical example of this is:<p><pre><code>    BEGIN {
        if(arbitrary_function()) {
            eval &quot;sub whatever() { }; 1&quot; or die $@;
        } else {
            eval &quot;sub whatever { }; 1&quot; or die $@;
        }
    }

    # The parsing of this line depends on the result of arbitrary_function()
    whatever  / 25 ; # / ; die &quot;this dies!&quot;;
</code></pre>
arbitrary_function() can be anything, so the only way to parse the rest of the program is to actually run arbitrary_function().
